export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "opener", "html": "<p>On October 1, 2025, a 400-tonne, 18-meter-diameter Dewar base — the largest vacuum component in China's fusion history — was set into the BEST pit in Hefei within a ≤2 mm tolerance, on a program committed to completing the device by end-2027.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"59\">[59]</sup> Its magnet steel was designed and mass-produced domestically (Box 10.1). What exists nowhere is a machine that can say what those first walls look like after five years of 14 MeV neutrons: IFMIF-DONES, fully operational around 2034.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"286\">[286]</sup> Between those dates, fusion qualification is simulation-or-nothing — the argument of this chapter.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s10-1-1", "html": "<p>As of 2026-07-17 the dated commitments read like a construction schedule, not a research roadmap. BEST began full assembly in May 2025 — one trade outlet reported it two months ahead of schedule — with ~500 t of localized CHSN01 jacket steel installed.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"287\">[287]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"288\">[288]</sup> CFETR was renamed CFEDR in June 2025 and upgraded from engineering test to demonstration reactor.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"289\">[289]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"290\">[290]</sup> ITER's Baseline 2024 moved deuterium–tritium operations to 2039 and swapped the beryllium first wall for tungsten, one material change the US Congressional Research Service prices at +$1B.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"291\">[291]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"292\">[292]</sup> Commonwealth Fusion Systems had SPARC ~75% built by April 2026 and filed the first fusion grid-interconnection request, a 400 MW ARC plant with Google contracted for half the output.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"293\">[293]</sup> Helion broke ground on its 50 MW Orion plant in July 2025 against a Microsoft PPA carrying penalties past 2028.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"294\">[294]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"295\">[295]</sup> TAE merged with Trump Media &amp; Technology Group in a &gt;$6B all-stock deal in December 2025.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"296\">[296]</sup> The US milestone program's $46M of federal money has drawn &gt;$350M of private follow-on capital.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"297\">[297]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"298\">[298]</sup> The magnet conductor inside the compact machines — REBCO tape above 20 T — is the superconductor problem of Chapter 4; this chapter takes the neutron side.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 10.1 — Program timeline vs. materials dependency (status as of 2026-07-17).</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Facility / milestone</th>\n<th>Date</th>\n<th>Status as of 2026-07-17</th>\n<th>Materials dependency</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>BEST (Hefei)</td>\n<td>Assembly May 2025; completion end-2027</td>\n<td>Dewar base installed 2025-10-01; on schedule <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"59\">[59]</sup></td>\n<td>500 t CHSN01 magnet jacket solved (Box 10.1); 0.17 MW/m² wall loading — blanket-module test bed, not a damage-accumulation machine <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"299\">[299]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>CFETR → CFEDR</td>\n<td>Renamed Jun 2025</td>\n<td>Design phase open; 1.5–3 GW, Q 15–30 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"289\">[289]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"290\">[290]</sup></td>\n<td>First device targeting fusion-spectrum fluence: ~10 dpa Phase I → ~50 dpa Phase II <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"300\">[300]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>ITER</td>\n<td>DT operations 2039</td>\n<td>Re-baselined 2024; Be→W first wall ≈ +$1B <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"291\">[291]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"292\">[292]</sup></td>\n<td>≤1.35 dpa full-life in W — cannot qualify DEMO's 45–100 dpa regime <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"301\">[301]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"302\">[302]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>CFS SPARC</td>\n<td>First plasma 2027</td>\n<td>Construction ~75% (Apr 2026) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"293\">[293]</sup></td>\n<td>REBCO magnets (Chapter 4 thread); burning-plasma physics, no qualification role</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>CFS ARC</td>\n<td>Grid filing Apr 2026</td>\n<td>400 MW PJM interconnection request; Google 50% offtake <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"293\">[293]</sup></td>\n<td>Explicitly &quot;its own volumetric neutron source&quot;: first wall/blanket fully replaced each maintenance cycle <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"286\">[286]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Helion Orion</td>\n<td>2028 PPA</td>\n<td>Plant groundbreaking Jul 2025; ≥50 MW to Microsoft, penalties attached <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"294\">[294]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"295\">[295]</sup></td>\n<td>D-<span class=\"math\">$^3$</span>He target cuts 14 MeV flux — materials exposure routed around by fuel choice <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"303\">[303]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>IFMIF-DONES</td>\n<td>Fully operational ~2034</td>\n<td>Under construction since Mar 2023; €202M via F4E (Feb 2026) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"304\">[304]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"305\">[305]</sup></td>\n<td>First 14 MeV high-flux source: ~20–30 dpa/yr in ~0.5 L; component-scale source not before late 2030s <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"286\">[286]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>TAE–TMTG</td>\n<td>Merger Dec 2025; plant siting 2026</td>\n<td>All-stock &gt;$6B; 50 MWe construction planned 2026 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"296\">[296]</sup></td>\n<td>p-<span class=\"math\">$^{11}$</span>B goal: weakest neutron-materials exposure, hardest physics <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"296\">[296]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>The pattern is the chapter in one line: every burning-plasma commitment lands before the first fusion-spectrum materials data — BEST, SPARC, and Orion all operate before DONES produces a qualified data point, and even CFEDR's ~10 dpa Phase I arrives after its design freeze. The private programs have read the same clock: ARC's replaceable blanket and the Helion/TAE low-neutron fuels are explicit admissions that qualified, long-lived in-vessel materials will not exist on their timelines.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"286\">[286]</sup> BEST's 0.17 MW/m² wall loading, about a sixth of ITER's peak, makes it a physics machine with blanket-module ports; the damage backlog shifts to CFEDR and the DEMO class.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"299\">[299]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"300\">[300]</sup> Until DONES, every licensing case and blanket design in this table rests on simulation chains validated only against fission and ion data.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s10-2", "html": "<p>Chapter 3 assigned fusion materials to taxonomy mode 9 — rare events and timescales — with scoreboard Row 7 (rare events / barriers) binding and Row 5's uncertainty quantification as the audit layer; Table 10.2 states the defining gaps.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 10.2 — The gaps simulation must bridge before IFMIF-DONES (~2034). dpa = displacements per atom; appm = atomic parts per million; DBTT = ductile–brittle transition temperature; RAFM = reduced-activation ferritic/martensitic steel.</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Error object</th>\n<th>Best available today (method)</th>\n<th>Service requirement</th>\n<th>Gap</th>\n<th>What the gap corrupts</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Cascade scale vs. service life</td>\n<td>NEP-ZBL MLIP: 8.1M atoms, 240 ps, one A100 GPU <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"15\">[15]</sup></td>\n<td>5-year first-wall/blanket life</td>\n<td>more than 15 orders of magnitude in time</td>\n<td>Long-time evolution handed to rate theory / kinetic Monte Carlo parameterized by the same error-prone potentials <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"306\">[306]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Damage validation</td>\n<td>Fission/ion data + ~20 dpa fusion-relevant RAFM database — one synthesis's &quot;20 dpa wall&quot; <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"6\">[6]</sup></td>\n<td>EU-DEMO second blanket: 50 dpa <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"7\">[7]</sup></td>\n<td>2.5–5<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> design extrapolation</td>\n<td>Structural design criteria (swelling, DBTT) beyond any data</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Helium co-production</td>\n<td>10–13 appm He/dpa in DEMO steel <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"307\">[307]</sup></td>\n<td>Fission-spectrum qualification basis</td>\n<td>~10<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> the 0.3–1 appm/dpa of fission <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"6\">[6]</sup></td>\n<td>He stabilizes voids and grain-boundary bubbles; fission data cannot qualify fusion structure</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>DBTT shift</td>\n<td><span class=\"math\">$\\Delta$</span>DBTT ≈ +100 °C at 2–3 dpa, 300 °C (ITER test-blanket end-of-life) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"33\">[33]</sup></td>\n<td>Water-cooled blanket: DBTT ≤100 °C <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"33\">[33]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"308\">[308]</sup></td>\n<td>Threshold crossed at ~1/25 of target fluence</td>\n<td>Hardening saturates; the He-driven embrittlement component does not <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"308\">[308]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Transmutation chemistry</td>\n<td>FISPACT: W → 3.8 at.% Re in 5 DEMO years <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"309\">[309]</sup></td>\n<td>Alloy identity stable across service</td>\n<td>End-of-life ≈ W-6Re-3Os, near σ/χ phase boundaries <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"302\">[302]</sup></td>\n<td>Qualified material ≠ end-of-life material; precipitation hardening and embrittlement <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"310\">[310]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Tritium fuel cycle</td>\n<td>~25 kg civilian stockpile (20–30 kg, decaying ~5.5%/yr) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"311\">[311]</sup></td>\n<td>55.8 kg/GW(thermal)·yr burn <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"312\">[312]</sup></td>\n<td>≈167 kg/yr per GWe vs kilogram-scale world supply</td>\n<td>Breeding blanket (breeding ratio &gt; 1, never demonstrated) becomes plant-critical</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Read together, the rows describe a compounding chain, not six numbers: the cascade row sets the source term, the dpa and helium rows say downstream evolution is validated only in the wrong neutron spectrum, the transmutation row says the material's identity drifts out of every training set during service, and the tritium row converts each materials error bar into a fuel-cycle error bar. Each row feeds the next — melting-point error biases surviving-defect counts, which bias cluster transport, which bias swelling and DBTT, which bias the blanket-replacement interval, which lands in the tritium margin. And the extrapolations are not waiting on a laboratory that exists somewhere: the 14 MeV high-flux volume that could check them opens around 2034 holding ~0.5 L — smaller than a coffee cup — at 20–30 dpa per year.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"286\">[286]</sup> An honest error budget must propagate the whole chain, not score each link separately.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s10-2-1", "html": "<p>A fusion-relevant cascade starts with a primary knock-on atom (PKA) of tens to hundreds of keV, melts a nano-region, and recrystallizes within 10–100 ps — across millions of atoms, a regime DFT-MD cannot touch.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"86\">[86]</sup> Machine-learned interatomic potentials (MLIPs) exist here because classical potentials failed: the first tungsten GAP fixed &quot;long-standing deficiencies&quot; in defect-cluster energetics and cascade dynamics.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"86\">[86]</sup> The frontier result — NEP-ZBL running 8.1 million atoms for 240 ps on one 40 GB A100 — is a genuine milestone, and even it finds thin-foil damage differing qualitatively from bulk: boundary conditions alone change defect outcomes.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"15\">[15]</sup> But 240 ps sits more than 15 orders of magnitude short of a five-year service life, so evolution is handed to rate theory or object kinetic Monte Carlo (OKMC) — a layer already caught wrong: standard rate theory predicted interstitial loops that all grow under irradiation; OKMC with elastic interactions matches experiment, at large compute cost.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"306\">[306]</sup> Residual errors compound the hand-off: GAP-class potentials still underestimate melting point and vacancy formation energy, biasing thermal-spike lifetime and surviving-defect counts — the source term for every higher-scale model.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"313\">[313]</sup> The only direct experimental anchor is threshold displacement energy, ~128 eV, &quot;in reasonable agreement with experimental results&quot;; surviving-defect numbers remain unvalidated against fusion spectra because no 14 MeV source exists.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"314\">[314]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s10-2-2", "html": "<p>Damage rates define the target: ITER ~0.3 dpa/yr, DEMO ~10 dpa/yr — about 45 dpa in tungsten after five full-power years.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"301\">[301]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"302\">[302]</sup> Europe's design strategy sets a starter blanket at ~20 dpa and a second at 50 dpa.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"7\">[7]</sup> Against 50 dpa, the fusion-relevant RAFM database ends near 20 dpa — one widely used industry synthesis calls it &quot;the 20 dpa wall,&quot; a single-source framing I flag as such; the underlying data are peer-reviewed: ΔDBTT ≈ +100 °C already at 2–3 dpa and 300 °C, an ITER test-blanket module's end-of-life, hardening saturating but the helium-driven component not.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"6\">[6]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"33\">[33]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"308\">[308]</sup> That is a 2.5–5<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> extrapolation fission data cannot fill, because the helium co-production rate is wrong by ~10<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> (Table 10.2).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"6\">[6]</sup> The first instrument that could, IFMIF-DONES, is under construction in Granada with €202M of new Fusion for Energy money announced in February 2026, reaches full operation around 2034, and delivers 20–30 dpa/yr in ~0.5 L — volumetric component testing &quot;not … before the late 2030s.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"304\">[304]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"286\">[286]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s10-2-3", "html": "<p>Even where time and dose could be simulated, composition cannot. UKAEA's review is blunt: atomistic capability stops at &quot;single elements or simple binary systems, such as Fe-Cr,&quot; while a real RAFM steel is Fe-Cr-W-V-Ta-C-N plus transmutant He and H, and bridging requires first-principles training configurations that multiply combinatorially per added species.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"203\">[203]</sup> A 2024 conference-scale effort reached force RMSE below 0.2 eV/Å for Fe-Cr-He on &quot;thousands of DFT calculations&quot; — proof of concept, yet still ~10<span class=\"math\">$\\times$</span> chemical accuracy against the 0.1–1 eV migration barriers that set defect kinetics.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"315\">[315]</sup> Transmutation makes the target move: under DEMO-like loading (2 MW/m², five years), FISPACT calculates ~3.8 at.% Re in pure tungsten; PPCS gives end-of-service armor of roughly 91W-6Re-3Os — near the σ/χ phase boundaries, where W-26wt%Re irradiated to 11 dpa already showed massive σ/χ precipitation with &quot;significant hardening and embrittlement.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"309\">[309]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"302\">[302]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"310\">[310]</sup> Equilibrium thermodynamics under-predicted that precipitation; SCK·CEN's hardening models needed post-hoc correction against test data that exist only for fission spectra — with the wrong transmutation rates.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"316\">[316]</sup> The material qualified at start of life is a different alloy at end of life, and no training set contains the destination.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s10-2-4", "html": "<p>The second bottleneck is fuel, and it is arithmetic before physics. The world civilian tritium stockpile is ~25 kg (estimates span 20–30 kg, decaying ~5.5%/yr); a fusion plant burns 55.8 kg per GW of fusion-thermal power per full-power year — ≈167 kg/yr for a 1 GWe plant at ~3 GW thermal (Abdou et al., Nucl. Fusion 2021; the figure survives a first-principles check).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"311\">[311]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"312\">[312]</sup> ITER's campaign alone will consume 12–20 kg, leaving &lt;4 kg at end of operations around 2052 on Abdou's accounting.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"311\">[311]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"312\">[312]</sup> Breeding ratio above 1 has never been demonstrated in an integrated blanket; breeder-ceramic tritium release under fusion-relevant burnup is largely a modeling exercise, DFT plus thermal-desorption calibration.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"317\">[317]</sup> Abdou's best case yields only &quot;slightly more tritium than it needs,&quot; so small inventory-prediction errors propagate into plant viability.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"312\">[312]</sup> Every error bar in §10.2.1–10.2.3 appears twice — once in structure, once in fuel.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s10-3", "html": "<p>Scoreboard Row 7 is the binding row, and its red status is the opening: no group has demonstrated migration-barrier MAE ≤ 40 meV (≈1 kcal/mol) across chemistries. The raw material for a fix exists — cascade-accurate MLIPs for elemental W and Fe are published (§10.2.1) — and the community's 2026 roadmap states the diagnosis: mean-error objectives &quot;may obscure catastrophic failures in rare but physically important regions of configuration space.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"108\">[108]</sup> What is missing is the validated hand-off: a cascade-to-OKMC chain whose every source term carries a calibrated error bar. The trust machinery exists — misspecification-aware uncertainty quantification already bounds the foundation model MACE-MPA-0's energy errors across the Materials Project database.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"93\">[93]</sup> My working bet: the sellable object here is not a potential but a qualification chain — DFT → MLIP → OKMC/rate theory → component, with an error budget a licensing case could cite before DONES produces data. It is within reach of demonstration at single-lab scale, because the work is measured in GPU-years, not reactors; the burden of proof sits with anyone claiming a bigger machine is the prerequisite.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s10-4", "html": "<p>The strongest honest case against this class is not schedule skepticism; it is that deuterium–tritium fusion is disqualified by its own particles. Daniel Jassby, 25 years in fusion neutron physics at Princeton: ~80% of D-T energy leaves as 14 MeV neutrons that damage and activate structure; tritium self-sufficiency is unproven and the arithmetic of §10.2.4 is brutal — &quot;This makes deuterium-tritium fusion reactors impossible.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"311\">[311]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"318\">[318]</sup> JASON adds that the fission fallback fails: at most ~1 tritium atom per fission, so 10 W of fission thermal power breeds fuel for 1 W of fusion — &quot;This makes no economic sense.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"319\">[319]</sup> Abdou gives DEMO a 5–14 kg startup inventory against &lt;4 kg post-ITER.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"312\">[312]</sup> I present this at full strength because program managers quote it, and because its first half is simply correct. Where I part from the conclusion: every load-bearing term — breeding margin, damage tolerance, inventory prediction — is a materials-development variable, not a physics constant. The Jassby position becomes right only if materials error bars stay unquantified forever; read carefully, it is the strongest argument <em>for</em> the qualification program of §10.3. Its valid corollary I concede: plants that burn before blankets are proven run on borrowed fuel — which is why the serious designs (ARC's replaceable blankets, Helion's D-<span class=\"math\">$^3$</span>He, TAE's p-<span class=\"math\">$^{11}$</span>B) already price materials ignorance into the architecture.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"286\">[286]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"296\">[296]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s10-5", "html": "<p>Beijing has made fusion a named growth industry: the 15th Five-Year Plan lists hydrogen and nuclear fusion energy among &quot;new economic growth points,&quot; and CSIS estimates Beijing has committed more than $6.5B to fusion since 2023 — a think-tank figure I cite as reported in trade coverage.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"22\">[22]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"320\">[320]</sup> The center of gravity is the Hefei cluster — BEST, the CRAFT complex, and a municipal build-out branded the &quot;trillion-yuan fusion city,&quot; with Fusion New Energy Co. (聚变新能) operating BEST.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"321\">[321]</sup> Box 10.1 records what that cluster already bought.</p>\n<p><strong>Box 10.1 — CHSN01: materials sovereignty executed on schedule — and the boundary of what it proves.</strong></p>\n<p>CHSN01, a modified Nitronic-50 austenitic steel (&quot;N50H&quot;), is the first steel designed for commercial fusion: 0.2% proof stress above <span class=\"math\">$1{,}500$</span> MPa at 4.2 K (average <span class=\"math\">$1{,}560$</span> MPa), ~30–33% elongation, fracture toughness 220 MPa·m<span class=\"math\">$^{1/2}$</span>, certified for 20 T and 1.3 GPa combined stress over 60,000 pulses — ~40% stronger than ITER's 316LN at equal toughness, whose jacket baseline sits below <span class=\"math\">$1{,}100$</span> MPa and &quot;fails to meet the demand&quot; of next-generation conductors.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"288\">[288]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"322\">[322]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"323\">[323]</sup> The localization is the point: ASIPP did not wait for an import license — ~500 t were delivered to BEST by mid-2025, including a 30 t continuous jacket ~5,000 m long, and BEST's 2027 completion plus CFEDR's magnet program guarantee a domestic order book inside a municipal fusion cluster built to absorb it.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"288\">[288]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"321\">[321]</sup> Two lessons, stated honestly. First, when the requirement is specified — a number at a temperature — materials development can be executed on program timelines, and sovereignty claims in materials are sometimes simply true. Second, CHSN01 solves the <em>cryogenic</em> problem, not the <em>neutron</em> problem: a magnet-jacket steel with no irradiation-damage role, and conflating the two is a common reporting error. Sovereignty on the neutron side cannot be manufactured ahead of the data — only simulated ahead of it.</p>\n<p>Washington's answer is institutional rather than metallurgical: on November 20, 2025, DOE created its first-ever Office of Fusion; the milestone program's $46M is now matched by &gt;$350M of private follow-on capital; and the FIRE Collaboratives add ~$220M for materials, blankets, and fuel-cycle research infrastructure.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"60\">[60]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"297\">[297]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"298\">[298]</sup> The Genesis Mission executive order frames fusion inside an AI-for-science platform spanning 17 national laboratories — a vehicle that could fund cascade-training-data generation at scale.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"324\">[324]</sup> I read the two systems as converging on one admission: neither owns the qualification-data problem before ~2034, and both are paying for the simulation layer that fills the wait.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s10-6", "html": "<p>This chapter feeds discovery chain 7: rare-event-validated MLIPs with calibrated uncertainty quantification → 50-dpa-qualified RAFM and first-wall materials plus breeding ceramics → commercial fusion blankets → firm clean power with tritium self-sufficiency. My position, stated once and defended above: fusion qualification is the most defensible simulation-led niche in this paper precisely because experiment is impossible until ~2034 — the buyer has no alternative instrument, so a validated error bar is the product.</p>\n<p>The fission adjacency strengthens it: the same error modes recur in systems already under construction. HALEU supply is a single-material gate — Centrus's 900 kg demonstration run completed June 2025, DOE awarded $2.7B of enrichment contracts in January 2026, initial capacity of 12 t/yr arrives with first new-cascade production in 2029 — against DOE-estimated 2035 demand of 50 t/yr, with only Russia and China producing HALEU commercially today.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"325\">[325]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"326\">[326]</sup> Molten-salt corrosion reproduces the fusion pattern: selective chromium dissolution in fluorides, tellurium intergranular attack, passivation unstable in the service medium, helium embrittlement of nickel-rich grain boundaries — chemistry outside every training set, licensing that demands uncertainty quantification.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"327\">[327]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"328\">[328]</sup> TerraPower's Natrium and Kairos's Hermes are in construction with those chemistry questions open.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"329\">[329]</sup> The laboratory that first sells a validated, uncertainty-quantified damage-and-corrosion chain into either market sets the evidentiary standard for both — and that standard, once set, is the moat.</p>\n" },
]
